83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
Minority Report
B-Engrossed
House Bill 4114
Ordered by the Senate March 3
Including House Amendments dated February 16 and Senate Minority
Report Amendments dated March 3
Sponsored by nonconcurring members of the Senate Committee on Judiciary: Senators MCLANE, THATCHER
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: The Act lets DOC workers help out with enforcing immigration laws for some
felons. (Flesch Readability Score: 65.7).
[Digest: The Act says that a person can sue a person who under color of law comes in property
without a warrant or an exception. (Flesch Readability Score: 62.6).]
[Creates a civil cause of action against certain individuals who under color of law enter certain
property without a warrant or an exception to the warrant requirement. Allows for an award of at-
torney fees to a prevailing plaintiff and, under certain circumstances, to a prevailing defendant.]
[Declares an emergency, effective on passage.]
Authorizes Department of Corrections employees to coordinate with a federal immi-
gration authority in carrying out any action concerning a person convicted of certain felo-
nies.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to law enforcement operations.
3 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
4 SECTION 1. Notwithstanding ORS 180.805, 181A.820 and 181A.822 to 181A.829 and any
5 other provision of Oregon law, all employees of the Department of Corrections may coordi-
6 nate with any federal immigration authority when the federal immigration authority is car-
7 rying out any action concerning a person convicted of a felony listed in ORS 137.700 (2),
8 aggravated murder, a felony sexual offense or any felony offense in which there was an ac-
9 tual or threatened physical injury to the victim.
10
